s norms). Hertel looks closely at struggles for human rights in two contexts: Bangladesh, where activists challenged the understanding of human rights central to an international campaign to prevent child labor in that country, and Mexico, where activists sought to broaden the scope of efforts to prevent discrimination against pregnant workers in their country. Hertel connects these unexpected challenges to a new wave of international advocacy, and thereby illuminates democratic struggles in the new global economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aHuman rights advocacyvCross-cultural studies. 0aHuman rightsxSocieties, etc. 0aPressure groupsvCross-cultural studies. 4aHuman Rights. 4aLabor History. 4aLegal History & Studies.  aActivism.  aChildren's rights.  aCivil rights.  aCollective bargaining.  aCross-cultural studies.  aDemocracy.  aEthnic minority rights.  aLGBTQ+ rights.  aadvocacy.  aanti-oppression.  acivil rights.  acommunity organizing.  across-border human rights campaigns.  acurrent affairs.  adisability rights.  aeconomic rights.  aequality.  aglobal human rights.  ahuman rights activists.  ahuman rights advocacy.  ahuman rights campaigns studies.  ahuman rights case studies.  ahuman rights studies.  ainterest groups.  ainternational advocacy.  ainternational policy campaigns.  ainternational policy case studies.  ainternational policy.  alabor issues.  alobbying.  alocal activists.  anongovernmental organizations.  apolitical activism.  apolitical science.  apolitics.  asocial movements.  astruggles for human rights.  atransnational advocacy campaigns.  atransnational allies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172